Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Allow ingredients to come to room temperature. Wash and dry produce.

In a large #bowl{}, whisk together half the @sour cream{1/2%tablespoon}, @eggs{2}, 1/3 cup @flour{1/3%cup}, 1/4 cup @milk{1/4%cup}, and a big pinch of @salt{pinch} until smooth.

> For 4 servings, use all the sour cream, three eggs, 1/2 cup flour, and 1/2 cup milk; save remaining egg for another use.

Place @butter{1%tablespoon} in a medium #ovenproof pan{}. Once oven is preheated, place pan on middle rack; heat until butter melts and starts to bubble.

> Watch carefully to avoid burning.

Once butter has melted, remove pan from oven and carefully swirl once to evenly coat bottom; pour in batter. Bake on middle rack until puffed and golden, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While Dutch baby bakes, dice half the @fresh mozzarella{4%ounces}(diced into ½-inch pieces).

> Save any remaining mozzarella for another use.

Roughly tear half the @prosciutto{2%ounces}(torn into thirds).

> It's OK if the pieces aren't perfect—it looks better that way! Save any remaining prosciutto for another use.

When Dutch baby has about ~{2%minutes} left, in a #medium bowl{}, toss @arugula{2%ounces} and half the diced mozzarella with a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoons}.

Top Dutch baby with as much arugula salad, torn prosciutto, and remaining diced mozzarella as you like. Season with @pepper{} and drizzle with @balsamic glaze{5%teaspoons}.

Serve family style directly from pan (or cut into wedges and divide between plates).

> Wash hands and surfaces after handling raw eggs. Consuming raw or undercooked eggs may increase your risk of foodborne illness.